{{For|the painting|The Road to Rome (painting)}} {{Infobox play | name = The Road to Rome | image = | image_size = | caption = | writer = [[Robert E. Sherwood|Robert Sherwood]] | chorus = | characters = | mute = | setting = [[Rome]] | premiere = {{Start date|1927|01|31|mf=yes}} | place = [[Playhouse Theatre]] | orig_lang = English | series = | subject = | genre = historical comedy | web = }}
'''''The Road to Rome''''' is a play by [[United States|American]] author [[Robert E. Sherwood|Robert Sherwood]]. The plot revolves around [[Hannibal]]'s attempt to capture [[Rome]] during the [[Second Punic War]]. It was Sherwood's first published play.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Road to Rome|last=Sherwood|first=Robert Emmett|publisher=Kessinger Publishing|url=https://www.amazon.com/Road-Rome-Robert-E-Sherwood/dp/1417927232/ref{{=}}sr_1_10?s{{=}}books&ie{{=}}UTF8&qid{{=}}1398317361&sr{{=}}1-10&keywords{{=}}robert+sherwood}}</ref>.
The play opened on Jan. 31, 1927 at the [[Playhouse Theatre]]<ref>https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-show/the-road-to-rome-7552</ref> in [[New York City]] and was considered a success<ref>http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1948/11/6/the-road-to-rome-pthe-newly-formed/</ref>, running until the next January. It was subsequently revived two months later at the same theater, running from Mar 21, 1928 until Jun 1929.<ref>https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-show/the-road-to-rome-7552</ref>
In 1955, the play was adapted for the screen in musical version by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] as ''[[Jupiter's Darling]]''.
